Prepping for Mapping in R

pacman::p_load("ggsn","leaflet","mapdata","maptools","OpenStreetMap","rgdal","tidyverse", "ggplot")
library(broom)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggmap)

Simple Map Example

For my simple map, I have constructed a visual representation of one of our study sites in Kentucky. The point represents the latitude and longitude where bat captures were conducted and the county is shaded in pink.

state <- map_data("state")
county <- map_data("county")
bat.point <- data.frame("x" = -87.6534, "y" = 36.6401)
ky <- county %>% 
  filter(region=="kentucky")

christianco <- county %>% 
  filter(region=="kentucky") %>% 
  filter(subregion=="christian")
ggplot() + geom_polygon(data = state, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
                        fill = "white", color="black") + 
           geom_polygon(data = ky, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
                        fill = "gray", color="black") + 
           geom_polygon(data = christianco, aes(x=long, y = lat, group = group),
                        fill = "pink", color="black") + 
           geom_point(data = bat.point, aes(x=x,y=y), color="black", size = 3) +
  coord_fixed(xlim = c(-90, -81),  ylim = c(36, 40), ratio = 1.2) + 
  xlab("Longitude") + ylab("Latitude") + ggtitle("Site 83A, Christian Co., KY")

Simple Map Example 2

For my second simple map, I have constructed a visual representation of all of our study sites in Kentucky. The points represents the latitude and longitude where bat captures were conducted.

ky.map <- openmap(c(36.7345833333,-87.6257361111),
                     c(36.6330527778,-87.8495222222), type='bing')

KY <- openproj(ky.map, projection = "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs")

ky.sites <- read.csv("ky.sites.csv")

autoplot.OpenStreetMap(KY) +
  geom_point(data=ky.sites, aes(x = X, y = Y, color=Name), size = 4, alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_text(data=ky.sites,aes(x=X,y=Y,label=Name), color="black", vjust=-0.60, size=4.01, fontface="bold") +
  geom_text(data=ky.sites,aes(x=X,y=Y,label=Name), color="white", vjust=-0.75, fontface="bold") +
  labs(x="Longitude", y="Latitude") + theme(legend.position = "none")

Interactive Map Example 1

For my first interactive map, I have constructed a visual representation of one of our study sites in Kentucky. The points represents the latitude and longitude where bat captures were conducted and it has been labeled by its site name.

siteOGR <- readOGR("C:/Users/skrueger/Desktop/Advanced Methods/Basic.mapping/Basic.mapping/ky.sites.kml")
## OGR data source with driver: KML 
## Source: "C:\Users\skrueger\Desktop\Advanced Methods\Basic.mapping\Basic.mapping\ky.sites.kml", layer: "ky.sites.kml"
## with 2 features
## It has 2 fields
ky_points <- as.data.frame(cbind(siteOGR@data,siteOGR@coords))
ky_points
##   Name Description coords.x1 coords.x2 coords.x3
## 1  10A              -87.7942   36.7122         0
## 2  83A              -87.6534   36.6401         0
ky_points[2] <- NULL
ky_points[4] <- NULL
colnames(ky_points) <- c("Name","X","Y")

leaflet(siteOGR) %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addMarkers(popup = siteOGR@data$Name) %>%
  addCircleMarkers(popup = siteOGR@data$Name,
                   label = siteOGR@data$Description,
                   weight = 2,
                   color = "grey",
                   fillColor = "pink",
                   fillOpacity = 0.7)

Interactive Map Example 2

For my second interactive map, I have constructed a topographic map of Rocky Mountain National Park (Long’s Peak).

leaflet() %>% 
  setView(lng = -105.6158365, lat = 40.2547069, zoom = 13) %>%
  addWMSTiles("https://basemap.nationalmap.gov/arcgis/services/USGSTopo/MapServer/WmsServer", layers = "0") %>%
  addMiniMap(zoomLevelOffset = -4) %>%
  addScaleBar()
